To turn this mock-up into a colorful website, you can use HTML and CSS to create a layout and style the content. Here's a basic example of how you could do this:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Joke Webpage</title>
  <style>
    body {
      background-color: #f2f2f2;
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    }

    .joke {
      font-size: 18px;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }

    .joke-number {
      font-size: 14px;
      color: #333;
    }

    .joke-text {
      font-size: 16px;
      color: #333;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Joke Webpage</h1>
  <div class="joke-container">
    <div class="joke-number">1</div>
    <div class="joke-text">Why was the math book sad? Because it had too many problems.</div>
    <div class="joke-number">2</div>
    <div class="joke-text">Why did the tomato turn red? Because it saw the salad dressing!</div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```
This example uses basic HTML and CSS to create a webpage with two jokes displayed in a container. You can replace the jokes with real jokes and adjust the styling to your liking. To make the website more colorful, you can add CSS styles for the background, text, and other elements.

To turn this mock-up into a colorful and interactive website, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's a basic outline of the code:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>My Joke Website</title>
  <style>
    /* Add CSS styles for the website */
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="joke-container">
    <h1>My Joke Website</h1>
    <p>
      <button id="f-joke">Funny Joke</button>
      <button id="j-joke">Joke</button>
      <button id="p-joke">Pun</button>
    </p>
    <div id="joke-container">
      <div id="f-joke-container"></div>
      <div id="j-joke-container"></div>
      <div id="p-joke-container"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    // Add JavaScript to replace the joke with a real joke
    const fJoke = document.getElementById("f-joke");
    const jJoke = document.getElementById("j-joke");
    const pJoke = document.getElementById("p-joke");

    fJoke.addEventListener("click", function() {
      document.getElementById("f-joke-container").innerHTML = "Why did the tomato turn red?";
    });

    jJoke.addEventListener("click", function() {
      document.getElementById("j-joke-container").innerHTML = "Why did the chicken cross the road?";
    });

    pJoke.addEventListener("click", function() {
      document.getElementById("p-joke-container").innerHTML = "Why did the scarecrow win an award?";
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```
This code creates a simple website with three buttons: "Funny Joke," "Joke," and "Pun." When a button is clicked, the corresponding joke container is updated with a real joke. The joke containers are styled with CSS, and the JavaScript code handles the button click events.

Please note that this is a basic example, and you may need to adjust the code to fit your specific requirements or add more features to the website.
